Overview and Instructions

In this checkpoint, you will import at least one table from your final project dataset into RStudio. I will confirm which dataset you will engage for your final project by 4PM on Tuesday September 28 unless youve submitted your assignment within the grace period (in which case, I will confirm later). You will write some R code to explore the observations and variables in the dataset. Then, referencing data documentation, you will study the definitions underlying the dataset, considering issues such as - What counts as an observation? How are observations counted or measured? How are observations categorized? In other words, in this assignment you will be performing an ethnography of data infrastructure - considering how the standards used to produce this dataset implicates what kinds of narratives we can draw from the data.

I will provide some examples of the kind of analysis Im expecting throughout the document using a dataset I work with quite a bit in my research - the Department of Homeland Securitys Prison Boundaries dataset. This dataset documents the locations and operating statuses of jails, prisons, and detention centers throughout the US.

Units of Observation

Any time we count something in the world, we are not only engaging in a process of tabulation; we are also engaged in a process of defining. If I count the number of students in a class, I first have to define what counts as a student. If someone is auditing the class, do they count? If I, as the instructor, am learning from my students, do I count myself as a student? As I make decisions about how Im going to define student, those decisions impact the numbers that I produce. When I change my definition of student, how I go about tabulating students also changes. Thus, as we prepare to count observations in a dataset, it is important to know how those observations are defined.

What makes each row in this dataset unique?

Identify the specific variables that uniquely identify each observation. Check to make sure that these values do not repeat in the dataset.

What does each row in your dataset represent?

In the prison_boundaries dataset, each row is what some might call a correctional facility, and what my collaborators and I refer to as a carceral facility (i.e.a prison, jail, or detention center).

Fill your response here.

How does that observation get defined in the data documentation?

For example, from the data documentation here, we learn that this dataset documents secure detention facilities When I run a Google search for a legal definition of a secure detention facility I learn that 42 USCS 5603 [Title 42. The Public Health And Welfare; Chapter 72. Juvenile Justice And Delinquency Prevention; Generally] defines a secure detention facility as follows:

any public or private residential facility which * (A) includes construction fixtures designed to physically restrict the movements and activities of juveniles or other individuals held in lawful custody in such facility; and * (B) is used for the temporary placement of any juvenile who is accused of having committed an offense or of any other individual accused of having committed a criminal offense.

Compare this to the more restrictive definitions of prisons, jails, and community confinement centers, according to 28 CFR 115.5 - General definitions:

Prison means an institution under Federal or State jurisdiction whose primary use is for the confinement of individuals convicted of a serious crime, usually in excess of one year in length, or a felony.

Jail means a confinement facility of a Federal, State, or local law enforcement agency whose primary use is to hold persons pending adjudication of criminal charges, persons committed to confinement after adjudication of criminal charges for sentences of one year or less, or persons adjudicated guilty who are awaiting transfer to a correctional facility.

Community confinement facility means a community treatment center, halfway house, restitution center, mental health facility, alcohol or drug rehabilitation center, or other community correctional facility (including residential re-entry centers), other than a juvenile facility, in which individuals reside as part of a term of imprisonment or as a condition of pre-trial release or post-release supervision, while participating in gainful employment, employment search efforts, community service, vocational training, treatment, educational programs, or similar facility-approved programs during nonresidential hours.

We also learn from the dataset documentation that military detention facilities are excluded.

As you are considering this, you should:

  • Look up legal definitions of the observation in your dataset according to the dataset producer, and others. How do they police the boundaries of what counts in these definitions?
  • Characterize the sample of observations in this dataset. In terms of the unit of observation, what gets included and excluded?
  • Consider how insights we derive from this dataset would change had a different definition been used.

Examine the residual categories

Residual categories are the catch-all categories for those things not easily classified. If you identified a residual category in your dataset, or a category with many missing values. Filter to those rows in the dataset and examine whats going on there. Can you discern anything about the observations that dont fit into the standard classification systems?

prison_boundaries %>%

Filtering to the NA rows in the SECURELVL column, I learn that security levels do not apply to most county jails.

According to what standards are these numbers reported?

Referring to the data documentation, I learn that representatives from the team at the Department of Homeland Security aggregated this dataset by referencing information about each facility recorded on the facilitys websites or other administrative sources. If the data about Population or Capacity was not recorded in this source, then it was listed as missing in the dataset. With this in mind, the accuracy and consistency of the numbers reported in these columns is largely dependent on which organization reported the numbers. There are no definitions for POPULATON or CAPACITY in the documentation, so Im unsure what counts as an incarcerated individual in these measures. (e.g.does a person in in-take count?) Because the numbers are reported from a number of different sources, there are likely inconsistencies in the dataset regarding the definitions of these variables; population reported by one facility could be different from population reported by another facility. You might think about how this relates to the discussion of translation in chapter 1 of Cooking Data.
